    {
      "num": 16,
      "text": "During an internal audit of the ISMS, the auditor discovers that management review meetings are conducted quarterly, but no documented evidence shows that the effectiveness of the information security measures is being evaluated against defined KPIs. According to ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.3, what is the PRIMARY deficiency?",
      "tag": "Management Review Effectiveness",
      "options": [
        "D. Management review documentation must be maintained for a minimum of seven years",
        "A. Management review fails to evaluate ISMS effectiveness against objectives and KPIs, violating clause 9.3 requirements",
        "B. Quarterly frequency is insufficient; monthly reviews are mandatory per ISO 27001:2022",
        "C. The organization lacks a formal risk assessment procedure preceding management review"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.3 requires management review to evaluate ISMS effectiveness, including achievement of information security objectives and performance against KPIs. Lack of documented evidence demonstrating this evaluation is a direct non-conformity.",
      "justification_wrong": "Frequency is organization-determined; risk assessment is separate from management review evaluation; retention periods vary by context."
    },
    {
      "num": 17,
      "text": "An organization implements automated monitoring of access logs but fails to establish procedures for identifying, documenting, and investigating anomalies. Which clause is most directly violated, and what corrective action is ESSENTIAL?",
      "tag": "Monitoring and Measurement Control Effectiveness",
      "options": [
        "B. Clause 8.4 is violated; the organization must redesign all access control mechanisms",
        "A. Clause 9.1 is violated; corrective action must define procedures for investigating detected security anomalies",
        "C. Clause 9.2 is violated; internal audit frequency must be increased to bi-weekly cycles",
        "D. Clause 7.5 is violated; operational planning procedures must be completely rewritten"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.1 requires monitoring and measurement to detect anomalies and non-conformities. Without investigation procedures, monitoring is ineffective. Corrective action must establish systematic investigation and response protocols.",
      "justification_wrong": "Access control redesign is disproportionate; audit frequency is independent of monitoring; operational planning is separate concern."
    },
    {
      "num": 18,
      "text": "Following a non-conformity detection during internal audit, management proposes implementing a new technical control and documenting lessons learned. However, they do not determine root cause or prevent recurrence systematically. Per ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.2, what is the CRITICAL gap?",
      "tag": "Corrective Actions and Root Cause Analysis",
      "options": [
        "B. Technical controls alone satisfy clause 10.2; lessons learned documentation replaces formal root cause analysis",
        "C. Non-conformities require immediate escalation to external auditors before corrective action planning",
        "A. Root cause analysis is mandatory; corrective actions must address causes and prevent recurrence, not just implement controls",
        "D. Corrective actions must be completed within 30 days regardless of complexity or organizational context"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.2 mandates that corrective actions address root causes and implement controls to prevent recurrence. Technical solutions without root cause analysis fail to address systemic issues and repeat non-conformities.",
      "justification_wrong": "Lessons learned supplement but do not replace root cause analysis; external auditor involvement is not prerequisite; timelines are organization-specific."
    },
    {
      "num": 19,
      "text": "An organization conducts internal audits covering 40% of control objectives annually on a rolling basis. During management review, senior management approves this approach, stating it reduces audit burden. What is the compliance status per ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.2?",
      "tag": "Internal Audit Scope and Frequency",
      "options": [
        "A. Non-conforming; clause 9.2 requires internal audits cover all processes and controls; management approval does not waive this requirement",
        "B. Conforming; rolling audits across multiple years satisfy clause 9.2 provided documentation is retained",
        "C. Conforming only if the organization demonstrates that 40% represents highest-risk controls",
        "D. Non-conforming; internal audits must be conducted quarterly without exception per normative requirements"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.2 requires internal audits to determine whether ISMS conforms to requirements. This implies comprehensive scope covering all control objectives and processes. Management approval cannot override this requirement; 40% coverage is insufficient.",
      "justification_wrong": "Rolling audits across years do not ensure current compliance; risk-based scope reduction lacks normative justification; quarterly frequency is not mandatory."
    },
    {
      "num": 20,
      "text": "During continuous improvement review, an organization identifies that detected non-conformities are increasing despite corrective actions. Analysis shows corrective actions address symptoms but root causes remain unresolved. Per ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.3, what must the organization prioritize?",
      "tag": "Continual Improvement and Effectiveness",
      "options": [
        "A. Strengthen root cause analysis methodology and verify corrective action effectiveness against root causes before implementation",
        "D. Redesign the ISMS framework and conduct full re-certification immediately",
        "B. Increase the number of corrective actions and implement additional technical controls to suppress non-conformities",
        "C. Accelerate internal audit frequency and shift focus entirely to compliance documentation"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.3 emphasizes continual improvement through effectiveness evaluation. Rising non-conformities despite corrective actions indicate systemic failure in root cause analysis. Organizations must strengthen analytical rigor and verify effectiveness before implementing actions.",
      "justification_wrong": "Symptom suppression via additional controls perpetuates ineffective approaches; audit frequency alone does not solve root causes; re-certification without improvement is counterproductive."
    },
    {
      "num": 21,
      "text": "During an internal audit of the ISMS, an auditor discovers that the organization's monitoring metrics do not align with the organization's risk appetite statement. According to ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.1, what should be the primary corrective action?",
      "tag": "Monitoring and Measurement Alignment",
      "options": [
        "B. Accept the non-conformity as monitoring metrics are independent of risk appetite",
        "C. Request external auditors to validate current metrics without modification",
        "A. Redefine monitoring and measurement processes to ensure alignment with risk appetite and organizational objectives, establishing clear KPIs",
        "D. Implement additional controls without adjusting monitoring parameters"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.1 requires monitoring and measurement to be appropriate to the organization's needs and objectives. Alignment with risk appetite ensures metrics directly support strategic goals and enable effective risk management decisions.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options B, C, D ignore the mandatory requirement in 9.1 for monitoring processes to support organizational objectives and enable determination of conformance. Metrics must be context-specific and risk-aligned."
    },
    {
      "num": 22,
      "text": "An organization conducts internal audits semi-annually. During a management review, the CISO proposes shifting to quarterly audits based on increased threat landscape. Under ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.2, what determines the appropriate audit frequency?",
      "tag": "Internal Audit Planning and Execution",
      "options": [
        "A. The organization's risk assessment results, significance of processes, and previous audit findings determine frequency and scope",
        "B. Industry best practice mandates quarterly audits for all organizations",
        "D. Audit frequency is fixed by ISO 27001 and cannot be modified",
        "C. External auditors must approve any changes to the internal audit schedule"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.2 requires audit frequency and scope based on the importance of processes, risk assessment, and previous audit results. Organizations determine appropriate frequency considering their context and risk profile.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options B and D contradict clause 9.2's requirement for risk-based determination. Option C incorrectly places approval authority with external auditors rather than the organization itself."
    },
    {
      "num": 23,
      "text": "Following an internal audit, multiple non-conformities are identified. The organization must determine if root cause analysis (RCA) is required for all findings. According to ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.2, when is RCA mandatory?",
      "tag": "Non-Conformity Evaluation and Correction",
      "options": [
        "D. RCA must be approved by external certification bodies before implementation",
        "B. RCA is performed only for non-conformities assessed as significant based on organizational risk criteria and impact assessment",
        "C. RCA is optional and only recommended for critical control failures",
        "A. RCA is required for all non-conformities, including minor findings, to ensure comprehensive corrective actions"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 10.2 requires organizations to determine whether root cause analysis is needed based on the non-conformity's significance and potential impact. Risk-based approach allows proportionate corrective actions aligned with organizational context.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A imposes unnecessary burden contradicting proportionality principle. Options C and D misinterpret clause 10.2's requirement for organizational judgment and authority in determining RCA necessity."
    },
    {
      "num": 24,
      "text": "An organization's management review identifies that corrective actions from a non-conformity raised 18 months ago have not been fully implemented due to budget constraints. Under ISO 27001:2022 clause 8.2 and 10.2, what is the primary concern?",
      "tag": "Corrective Action Effectiveness and Timeline",
      "options": [
        "D. Only external auditors can authorize extensions to corrective action timelines",
        "C. Corrective actions become invalid after 12 months and must be re-initiated from scratch",
        "B. The organization must evaluate residual risk, establish realistic timelines, and ensure corrective actions address root causes before closure",
        "A. Budget constraints justify indefinite deferment of corrective actions without reassessment"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clauses 8.2 and 10.2 require organizations to evaluate residual risk and ensure corrective actions are timely, effective, and address root causes. Budget constraints do not eliminate this obligation; risks must be actively managed and justified.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A violates mandatory corrective action requirements. Option C incorrectly assumes validity expiration. Option D improperly delegates organizational responsibility to external parties."
    },
    {
      "num": 25,
      "text": "During management review, the organization analyzes performance data showing a 15% increase in security incident reports. Management must determine if this represents improvement or deterioration. According to ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.3, what analysis approach is required?",
      "tag": "Performance Analysis and Continuous Improvement",
      "options": [
        "A. Treat all incident increases as negative performance indicators and immediately implement additional restrictive controls",
        "B. Analyze trends contextually, examining root causes, detection effectiveness, and control maturity to determine if increase reflects improved detection or actual security degradation",
        "D. External consultants must validate all performance data interpretations before management decisions",
        "C. Ignore incident metrics if they conflict with predetermined improvement targets"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.3 requires analysis of monitoring and measurement results to determine ISMS performance and effectiveness. Increased incident reporting may indicate improved detection capability rather than security degradation—context matters for informed decisions.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A assumes causality without analysis, violating clause 9.3's requirement for evidence-based performance evaluation. Options C and D reject necessary analysis and delegate organizational accountability inappropriately."
    },
    {
      "num": 26,
      "text": "During an internal audit of the ISMS, the auditor discovers that KPIs for information security performance are not aligned with organizational objectives. According to ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.1, what is the primary requirement for monitoring and measurement?",
      "tag": "Performance Evaluation and KPIs",
      "options": [
        "C. Implement only quantitative metrics that demonstrate compliance with control objectives",
        "B. Conduct quarterly audits to identify all deviations from baseline security metrics",
        "D. Use external consultants to validate all KPIs quarterly",
        "A. Establish and maintain procedures to monitor, measure, analyze and evaluate ISMS performance against organizational objectives and requirements"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 9.1 requires establishing procedures for monitoring and measurement that evaluate ISMS performance against organizational objectives. KPIs must align with organizational goals to ensure meaningful assessment of information security effectiveness and contribution to business outcomes.",
      "justification_wrong": "Alternatives B, C, D are incorrect: B implies excessive audit frequency not mandated; C limits metrics inappropriately; D requires external validation not required by normative clause 9.1."
    },
    {
      "num": 27,
      "text": "An organization discovers during management review (clause 10.3) that incident response times have degraded significantly over six months. The review team must document findings. What should be the primary focus when determining corrective actions?",
      "tag": "Management Review and Corrective Actions",
      "options": [
        "B. Immediately replace the incident response team with external specialists",
        "C. Increase monitoring frequency to detect incidents faster without analyzing underlying causes",
        "D. Implement additional controls without evaluating current control effectiveness",
        "A. Root cause analysis to address systemic gaps in processes, resources, or competence related to incident response effectiveness"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 10.2 requires that corrective actions address root causes of nonconformities. For degraded incident response, systemic analysis of processes, resource allocation, and competence is essential to prevent recurrence and improve ISMS effectiveness sustainably.",
      "justification_wrong": "B assumes resource replacement without investigation; C treats symptoms not causes; D adds controls without evaluating necessity. None align with clause 10.2 root cause and corrective action requirements."
    },
    {
      "num": 28,
      "text": "During internal audit planning per ISO 27001:2022 clause 9.2.1, an auditor notes that certain high-risk control areas have not been audited in 18 months due to resource constraints. What adjustment should be made to the audit schedule?",
      "tag": "Internal Audit Planning and Risk-Based Scheduling",
      "options": [
        "D. Extend audit cycles to three years for all controls to reduce workload",
        "C. Audit only areas where management reports issues to conserve resources",
        "A. Increase audit frequency for high-risk areas based on risk assessment; ensure complete coverage aligned with organizational risk profile and control maturity",
        "B. Maintain current schedule; resource constraints justify delayed audits of low-criticality controls"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Clause 9.2.1 requires internal audits based on importance and risk. High-risk areas demand frequent audits. Resource constraints do not justify deferred audits of critical controls; priority allocation ensures effective ISMS oversight and control validation.",
      "justification_wrong": "B accepts non-compliance; C creates audit gaps in untested areas; D reduces audit effectiveness. None meet clause 9.2.1 risk-based audit frequency requirements for material controls."
    },
    {
      "num": 29,
      "text": "An organization's nonconformity log shows recurring issues with access control provisioning and deprovisioning (Annex A, control 5.3). According to clause 10.2, what should the corrective action framework address to prevent recurrence?",
      "tag": "Nonconformity Management and Systemic Prevention",
      "options": [
        "B. Issue disciplinary actions to employees responsible for manual access provisioning",
        "A. Evaluate and address root causes: inadequate procedures, insufficient competence, weak controls, or governance gaps; implement preventive measures across the ISMS",
        "D. Document the nonconformity and close it after implementing a single detective control",
        "C. Implement only technical compensating controls without reviewing process design"
